        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity:

There is no precedent for this type of observation because a broadband spectral line survey toward a collisional ring system has never taken place.  However, given the line intensity of the CO 1-0 transition was 51 mJy/beam as reported by the IRAM 30 m observation, we are assuming the molecular gas distribution to extend over 5 beam elements along the collisional ring and thus a peak line intensity of 10 mJy.  Therefore, given the expected sensitivity of 0.02 mJy at the highest spatial resolution, we conservatively anticipate detecting the CO 1-0 at a SNR of better than 20.

Imaging:

We have requested an angular resolution of 0.5".  This resolution makes ideal and efficient use of ALMA resources by 1) providing more than five times the spatial resolution across the anticipated extent of the CO emission region, 2) not requiring use of the ACA to recover the large-scale structure, and 3) requiring only a single 12-m configuration for these observations.  The target sources (~5") easily fit within the primary beam of the array, so we anticipate no issues with sensitivity loss. The UV coverage of the region will be robust over the course of the on-source integration.

Correlator Setup:

As outlined in the Scientific Justification, we have chosen to target nearly the entire ALMA Band 3 as this provides an ideal mix of strong low energy molecular transitions. In addition to CO, the spectral line survey will cover:  C2H 87.28 - 87.33, 87.40 - 87.45, HNCO 87.9252 (404 − 303), HCN 88.6316 (1-0), HCO+ 89.1885 (1-0), HNC 90.6636 (1-0), HC3N 90.9790 (10-9), 
100.0764 (11-10) &amp; 109.1736 (12-11), CH3CN 91.96-91.99 (5 − 4) &amp; 110.33-110.39 (6 − 5), N2H+ 93.1734-93.1740 (1-0), CH3OH 95.91-97.58 (2-1) and multiple other transtions, CS 97.9810 (2-1), 13CO 110.2014 (1-0), CN 113.12-113.59 (multiple) and many other possible molecular species.

Calibration:

We have selected system-defined calibration as suggested.

Bandpass accuracy:

We anticipate no issues arising in this area.  In addition, a member of the observing team have helped commission the spectral line observing mode for the observatory.

Scheduling/Time Constraints:

We require no special scheduling or time considerations.

Data rate:

We do not exceed the recommended data rate for these observations.

Special constraints:

Our total overheads constitute &lt;25% of the total observational time and have moderate integration times.

  </prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
