    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>Understanding the triggering of star formation in galaxies relies heavily on the timescale over which molecular clouds are created (and subsequently destroyed), but since most star-forming galaxy disks are very confused regions, the processes of cloud and star formation are generally impossible to separate.  We propose that given ALMA’s enormous sensitivity at high spatial resolution to a large spectral bandwidth, for the first time, we will be able to identify possible “chemical clocks” tied to the evolution of the molecular gas as well as a host of new ISM diagnostic tracers present in the extreme environments of collisional ring galaxies.  This proposal will resolve molecular transitions that can be used as shock and extreme environment tracers in a spectral survey of Arp 147 - the prototypical collisional ring galaxy.  The system is ideal to study the concept of “chemical clocks” given its recent and major, but relatively simple and well modeled, star formation trigger and will provide a proxy to the study of other collisional ring systems as well as star formation in more confused galaxy disks.</prp:abstract>
